  <p>You load up the heater, get a fire going, and within minutes smoke is pushing back into the room. Or the fire keeps dying no matter how much you feed it. Or it burns fine but the room barely warms up. Poor draw is one of the most common complaints Melbourne homeowners bring to us every year — and in the majority of cases, the fix is straightforward once you know what you're dealing with.</p>

  <h2>What "Draw" Actually Means</h2>

  <p>Draw refers to the upward airflow through the flue that pulls combustion gases out of the firebox and up through the chimney. Good draw creates a strong, consistent draft that feeds oxygen to the fire, allows it to burn hot and efficiently, and vents all smoke and gases safely outside. Poor draw means restricted airflow — and that restriction has to go somewhere, which is usually back into your room.</p>

  <h2>The Most Common Causes of Poor Draw</h2>

  <h3>1. Blocked or Heavily Sooted Flue</h3>

  <p>This is by far the most common cause, particularly at the start of winter after months of non-use. Creosote and soot accumulate on the flue walls over each heating season. Enough buildup and the internal diameter of the flue shrinks significantly, restricting airflow. A flue that was 150mm wide when installed might effectively be 80–90mm after a few seasons without cleaning.</p>

  <p>If your heater drew well last season but is struggling now, or if you notice the problem getting worse over the course of winter, a dirty flue is almost certainly the cause. This requires a professional clean — it's not something you can address from inside the firebox.</p>

  <h3>2. Bird Nest or Debris Blockage</h3>

  <p>Melbourne's spring and summer are prime nesting season, and an unused chimney flue is an attractive spot for starlings, sparrows and other birds. A nest built over summer can partially or completely block the flue. You might hear scratching or chirping from the flue during the warmer months, or notice twigs and debris falling into the firebox.</p>

  <p>A blocked flue from a nest is dangerous — don't attempt to burn through it. The nest material is dry and highly flammable. Get it professionally cleared before lighting any fires.</p>

  <h3>3. Cold Flue — Particularly on First Light</h3>

  <p>This one surprises people. On a cold morning, the air inside a cold flue can actually be denser than the air outside, which means it wants to flow downward rather than up. When you light the fire, you're fighting against this cold air column before the flue warms up and the draw establishes itself.</p>

  <p>You can help this by warming the flue before lighting the main fire. Roll up a piece of newspaper, light it, and hold it inside the firebox near the throat of the flue for 30–60 seconds before loading the heater. This warms the air at the base of the flue and helps establish the upward draft. Once the flue is warm, draw usually establishes quickly.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Cold flue draw issues are most common on very cold mornings, in heaters that haven't been used for several days, and in flues that run on an outside wall (where the flue is exposed to cold air). An insulated flue liner helps significantly with this.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>4. Negative Air Pressure in the House</h3>

  <p>Modern homes are increasingly well-sealed for energy efficiency — double-glazed windows, draft-proofed doors, exhaust fans in kitchens and bathrooms. In a tightly sealed house, a wood heater draws in air to feed combustion, which can create negative pressure inside. If the house is more airtight than the flue can compensate for, the heater struggles to draw.</p>

  <p>Test this by cracking a window slightly near the heater when you're having draw problems. If the fire immediately improves, negative air pressure is the culprit. The fix is to ensure the room has adequate air supply when the heater is in use — a purpose-built air vent near the heater is the proper solution.</p>

  <h3>5. Closed or Partially Closed Flue Damper</h3>

  <p>Many older fireplaces and some wood heaters have a damper — a metal plate that can be adjusted to control airflow through the flue. If it's been left partially or fully closed from the previous season, poor draw is the result. Check that the damper is fully open before lighting any fires. On older systems the damper mechanism can also seize up or corrode over time.</p>

  <h3>6. Incorrect Air Intake Settings on the Heater</h3>

  <p>Freestanding wood heaters have primary and secondary air controls — usually levers or dials on the front. If both are closed or nearly closed, the fire will starve of oxygen and draw will suffer. When lighting, both controls should typically be fully open. Once the fire is established and burning hot, you can throttle back to maintain a slower burn.</p>

  <p>Refer to your heater's manual if you're unsure of the correct settings. Each brand and model is slightly different.</p>

