  <h2>When the Problem Is More Serious</h2>

  <p>If you've ruled out all of the above and the heater still draws poorly after a professional clean, the issue may be structural. Common structural causes include a flue that's too short (insufficient height to create adequate draft), a flue diameter that's too small relative to the firebox opening, deteriorated or collapsed flue liner sections, or a poorly designed bend or offset in the flue run.</p>

  <p>These are less common than the straightforward blockage and buildup issues — but they do exist, particularly in older Melbourne homes where the system may have been altered or repaired over the decades. A professional will flag these during the inspection and can advise on options.</p>

  <h2>The Quick Diagnostic Checklist</h2>

  <p>Before calling a professional, run through these in order. Tick off the easy fixes first, then book a clean if the problem persists:</p>

  <p><strong>Damper fully open?</strong> Check and open if not.</p>
  <p><strong>Air intake controls open?</strong> Open both fully when lighting.</p>
  <p><strong>Cold flue?</strong> Warm it with a rolled newspaper before lighting the main fire.</p>
  <p><strong>Tight house?</strong> Crack a nearby window and see if draw improves.</p>
  <p><strong>Visible debris or nest material?</strong> Don't light — get it cleared first.</p>
  <p><strong>None of the above?</strong> Book a professional clean. A sooted flue is almost certainly the cause.</p>

  <h2>How Long Does a Flue Clean Take?</h2>

  <p>For a freestanding wood heater and flue, a professional clean takes 45–75 minutes. That includes the full flue from firebox to cap, soot and creosote removal, blockage check, and a verbal condition report. In most cases, draw is restored completely and the difference is noticeable from the very first fire after the clean.</p>
